Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Antigua and Barbuda. The authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus. See local measures below for more details.
VC Bird International Airport is currently closed to routine commercial flights until 23 April. Cargo and flights to repatriate foreign nationals are still permitted. Barbuda Airport is closed other than for emergency, cargo, or rescue flights. See Return to the UK section for more information.
All maritime ports in Antigua and Barbuda are currently closed other than to emergency or cargo vessels. This includes yachts and makes no exception to the flag of the vessel nor nationality or residential status of those on board.
For permitted flights and maritime vessels, the 26 March government of Antigua and Barbuda announcement that, until further notice, any non-Antigua and Barbuda national with a travel history in Canada, China, any country in Europe, Iran, South Korea, Japan, Singapore, and the USA within 28 days will not be permitted entry into Antigua and Barbuda still applies.
Local Measures
On 31 March the government of Antigua and Barbuda announced that the state of emergency which began on 25 March would last until 23 May. On 15 April the government of Antigua and Barbuda announced that the complete lockdown from 2 April is extended until 23:59 on 22 April.
There are certain exemptions for those providing or seeking emergency support and supplies, and to undertake exercise.
No more than two people may travel in a motor vehicle at any one time. All beaches in Antigua and Barbuda are closed.
People under the age of 18 may only leave their homes if they are accompanied by a parent or legal guardian.
People may undertake exercise in open fields or at the side of roads between 07:00 and 12:00 each day. They may be accompanied by one person providing they observe a distance of six feet.
All people out on essential business, including when in motor vehicles, or undertaking exercise must wear masks that cover the nose and mouth.
All non-essential services such as bars, nightclubs, and restaurants are closed and all social gatherings are prohibited.
Essential services such as food shops, pharmacies, and hardware stores are operating with reduced opening hours.
Public-facing government offices are also restricting opening hours and visitors.
Failure to comply with the state of emergency regulations will result in either a fine of XCD5000 and/or six months imprisonment.
The Antigua and Barbuda Emergency Medical Service are asking the public to call the COVID-19 inquiries hotline on 462 6843 if they suspect they might have contracted the virus, been exposed to or any other matters relating to the virus. The public are asked to call the hotline and not visit a healthcare facility unless instructed to.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
